Quoting hal@cco.caltech.edu (Hal Finney) in article <1jemknINN1rv@gap.caltech.edu>:
>How about this for a statement of the problem:
>
>Communicants are A and B, spoofer is C.  All messages between A and B
>pass through C, who can change them.  A wishes to send a one bit message M
>to B without C discovering M.  B and C initially share all information
>(anything B knows, C knows).  (Obviously A knows M, while B and C do not.)
>
>	A <-----> C <-----> B

I don't think this is precise enough.  "All messages between A and B
pass through C, who can change them."  Change them?  What about
substituting "To be or not to be" for "She should have died hereafter"?

You need to codify the separation between the protocol and the message
content.
